	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-jonny bypostauthor even thread-even depth-1" id="li-comment-30386">
		<div id="comment-30386">
			<div class="comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/2e8b35a375103c6b2d65dcf9947e39d7?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />				<cite class="fn">jonny</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>			</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
			
			<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://jonnyelwyn.co.uk/thunderbolt/which-harddrive-should-i-buy-for-video-editing/#comment-30386">
				February 19, 2013 at 3:00 pm</a>			</div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->

			<div class="comment-body"><p>I just thought I&#8217;d add a thought to this post on something I haven&#8217;t made quite crystal clear although it&#8217;s kind of obvious when you think about it. </p>
<p>If you&#8217;re going to have two drives, with one as a back up of the other, you will need to keep copying across any new assets etc that you have created that day, backing up project files etc so that everything is in two places at once. Ideally these two drives would end up in physically different locations to protect against loss or theft.</p>
<p>If you have a raided drive, it will be doing this mirroring for you (in effect) but then everything is physically in one location if your suite/house/hotel room/boat gets broken into or catches fire etc etc.</p>
</div>

