	<li class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1" id="li-comment-60577">
		<div id="comment-60577">
			<div class="comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/9cc1bbf0fbf6bf4da82fa5b7e48ea932?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />				<cite class="fn"><a href="http://RethinkHQ.com" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push(['_trackEvent','outbound-commentauthor','http://RethinkHQ.com']);"  rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Jon</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>			</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
			
			<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://jonnyelwyn.co.uk/thunderbolt/which-harddrive-should-i-buy-for-video-editing/#comment-60577">
				June 15, 2013 at 12:59 pm</a>			</div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->

			<div class="comment-body"><p>Hi Jonny good article. Not sure if you mentioned this but most drive read write slows down at about 75% capacity. This need to be factored in when working out how much space you will need.<br />
On another note, some drive run at 10000rpm and some at 15krpm. These are more expensive but when R/W speed is everything then often it&#8217;s better to buy a working drive with faster drive ad then a backup drive with slower cheaper drives.<br />
I stand to be corrected on some of there stats, I&#8217;m not an expert just an user.</p>
<p>And I don&#8217;t like LaCie Drives. Unreliable. I have 5 assorted faulty LaCie drives. Waste of money.</p>
</div>

